  <text xml:lang="ta" type="edition">
    <body>
      <div xml:id="KT230-kilavi">
        <p type="edition">valitākak kūṟik kuṟai nayappittatu. </p>
        <p type="translation" xml:lang="en">Speaking firmly [and] granting the request. </p>
      </div>

      <div xml:id="KT230">
        <lg type="edition">
          <l> amma vāḻi tōḻi koṇkaṉ</l>
          <l> ṟāṉatu tuṇikuva ṉallaṉ yāṉeṉ</l>
          <l> pētai maiyāṟ peruntakai keḻumi</l>
          <l> nōtakac ceytatoṉ ṟuṭaiyēṉ kollō</l>
          <l> vayaccuṟā vaḻaṅkunī rattañ</l>
          <l> ciṉṉā ḷiṉṉa varavaṟi yāṉē.</l>
        </lg>

        <lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">

          <l>Alas, oh friend, the man from the sea,</l>
          <l>he does not decide <note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">tuṇi-tal </term> ("to
            resolve, determine" etc., DEDR 3305) might here also have the flavour of the second <term xml:lang="ta">tuṇi-tal</term> ("to dare, venture"; DEDR 3306), i.e. a note of daring
            resolution, though here once again the question arises whether we really ought to accept
            two lemmas.</note> on this.</l>
          <l rend="indent8">Do I,</l>
          <l rend="indent2">with my folly, filled by a great [sense of] being suited,<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">taku</term> is, with all its derivations, a
            semantically problematic item. This phrase <term xml:lang="ta">perum takai keḻumi</term>
            can refer to their being exceptionally fit for one another. T.V.G. explains the phrase
            as "taking special rights", i.e. presumably "taking liberties [with him]" (see 3b).</note></l>
          <l>possess something which gave [him] pain?<note place="foot">The exact syntax and the
            meaning of this whole line are dubious. For <term xml:lang="ta">nō-taka</term> see note
            on KT 197.1. I wish to take it as an adverbial infinitive: "in a way that it is fit [to
            feel] pain". Then the whole might be taken literally: "Is with me (<term xml:lang="ta">
            uṭaiyēṉ</term>) something that has been done such that it was fit [to feel] pain
            [about]?"</note></l>
          <l rend="indent2">On the road by the water frequented by strong sharks,</l>
          <l>a few days thus he just didn't come.<note place="foot">
              <term xml:lang="ta">varavu aṟiyāṉ</term> : the meaning of <term xml:lang="ta">aṟi-tal</term>
            in this kind of phrase is probably just a kind of emphasis on his not coming. T.V.G.
            explains it accordingly as being synonym to <term xml:lang="ta">vārāṉ </term> "he didn't
            come". (See also KT 302.8; in KT 233.6, 242.6, however, it is still possibly to
            understand similar phrases literally.)</note></l>

          <lg type="alternate" sameAs="3b" resp="#TVG">
            <l>do I by my folly, taking liberties [with him],</l>
          </lg>

        </lg>
      </div>
    </body>
